4) Session & Token Model

4.1 Access token (JWT)

Purpose: authorize API calls

Properties:
	•	TTL: 15 minutes
	•	Included as Authorization: Bearer <token>

Claims (minimum):
	•	sub = userId
	•	tenantId = selected tenant context
	•	role = role within that tenant
	•	iat, exp
	•	optional: jti, membershipId

Storage on client:
	•	In memory (recommended for SPA)

4.2 Refresh token (opaque)

Purpose: obtain new access tokens without re-login

Properties:
	•	TTL: 14 hours
	•	Stored server-side hashed in DB
	•	Stored client-side as httpOnly secure cookie (recommended)

Cookie properties:
	•	HttpOnly; Secure; SameSite=Lax; Path=/auth/refresh

Refresh rotation (locked)
	•	Each successful refresh:
	•	issues a new refresh token
	•	revokes the prior one

Fixed window behavior:
	•	Refresh token expiry is a fixed 14-hour window (no UX alerts).

⸻

5) Refresh Token Storage (DB)

5.1 refresh_tokens

Purpose: server-side session tracking and rotation

Fields:
	•	id (UUID, PK)
	•	user_id (UUID, FK → users.id)
	•	tenant_id (UUID, FK → tenants.id)
	•	token_hash (TEXT) — hash of opaque refresh token
	•	expires_at (TIMESTAMPTZ)
	•	revoked_at (TIMESTAMPTZ, nullable)
	•	rotated_from_id (UUID, nullable, FK → refresh_tokens.id)
	•	created_at (TIMESTAMPTZ)

Indexes:
	•	(user_id, tenant_id)
	•	(expires_at)
	•	unique on token_hash

