6) Multi-tenant Login & Tenant Selection

6.1 Login behavior

A user logs in with email/password.

System finds all ACTIVE memberships for that user.

Cases:
	1.	0 memberships → reject (or “no access”)
	2.	1 membership → issue tenant-scoped access+refresh tokens
	3.	>1 memberships → require tenant selection

6.2 Tenant selection

When multiple memberships exist, user selects which tenant to enter.

Recommended: use a short-lived pre-auth token (~5 minutes) returned from login to authorize selection.

After selection:
	•	issue tenant-scoped access+refresh tokens for chosen tenant

⸻

7) Tenant Switching

7.1 Switch tenant API

User can switch tenant from inside the portal.

Flow:
	•	validate membership exists and is ACTIVE for target tenant
	•	issue new tenant-scoped access token
	•	rotate/replace refresh token for target tenant

Recommended behavior:
	•	revoke previous tenant’s refresh token on switch (clean separation)

⸻

8) Invite-by-link Flow

8.1 Invite creation (admin-only)

Admin invites staff/editor by email.

Invite record stored and email link is generated.

invites table

Fields:
	•	id (UUID, PK)
	•	tenant_id
	•	email
	•	role (STAFF or EDITOR)
	•	token_hash
	•	expires_at
	•	accepted_at (nullable)
	•	created_by_user_id
	•	created_at

Constraints:
	•	invite token single-use
	•	expiry enforced (recommended 48h)

8.2 Invite acceptance

User clicks invite link with token.

Acceptance behavior:
	•	validate token and expiry, ensure not accepted
	•	if user exists:
	•	activate membership (or create if missing)
	•	if user does not exist:
	•	create user + set password
	•	create membership as ACTIVE
	•	mark invite accepted
	•	issue tenant-scoped tokens immediately (user enters tenant)

⸻

9) Password Reset-by-link Flow

9.1 Reset request

User submits email.

System response is always generic to prevent enumeration:
	•	return { ok: true } always

If user exists:
	•	create reset token record
	•	email reset link

password_resets table

Fields:
	•	id (UUID, PK)
	•	user_id
	•	token_hash
	•	expires_at
	•	used_at (nullable)
	•	created_at

9.2 Reset confirmation

User submits token + new password.

Behavior:
	•	validate token (not expired, not used)
	•	update password hash
	•	mark token used
	•	revoke all refresh tokens for user (recommended)

⸻

10) Security & Edge Cases (Locked)

10.1 Membership disabled mid-session

Goal: immediate lockout.

Rule:
	•	If membership status becomes DISABLED, user loses access immediately (even if access token has time left).

Implementation:
	•	Central policy checks membership status on every request (DB or cached).
	•	If not ACTIVE → deny.

10.2 Refresh token reuse after rotation

Goal: treat as token theft.

Rule:
	•	If a rotated (revoked) refresh token is presented again:
	•	revoke all refresh tokens for that {userId, tenantId}
	•	clear refresh cookie
	•	return 401 forcing re-login

